The pilot of ASH6022 originally reported a bird strike at approximately the DCA315020, which is N of Sterling, VA just W of the Trump National Golf course.   The aircraft was heading S at altitude 2,700 feet setting up for a landing on runway 19L.  No injuries or damage to aircraft were reported.  The strike occurred about 0025 Zulu and aircraft landed 0029 Zulu without incident.  The pilot reported a bird strike, but upon inspection of the aircraft on the ground, the crew could not locate any normal signs of a bird strike, such as blood, feathers or anything biological.  The crew upon reflection said the strike did not sound like a bird which is usually a soft thud, but it sounded more like a sharp crack like a baseball bat.   Because of the lack of biological evidence and the sharp sound of impact, the crew believes they hit a UAS.  Fairfax County PD is being notified of this incident.  0154:  The Washington Operations Center (WOC) called the FAA DEN position and told them Mesa Airlines (ASH) had a maintenance crew re examine the aircraft and the airline is now changing this incident to Bird Strike.  The airline did not pass to the FAA why they changed this report.  NFA.

2155 EDT / 0155 UTC 8/23/2021
Chicago OHare (ORD) ATCT/Chicago TRACON (C90)  Sunday, August 22, 2021 at 6:25 p.m. CDT:  (Envoy) ENY3961/E170 departed the ORD Airport on Runway 9C and collided with a Unmanned Aerial Vehicle (UAV) approximately 1 NM from the departure end.  ENY3961 declared an emergency, returned to the ORD Airport, and landed without incident.  (JetBlue) JBU2112/E170, a prior departure from Runway 9C, had reported to ORD ATCT they had observed an UAV on departure.  In a post event aircraft inspection, it was reported that drone materials were found in the aircraft engine.  ATC services were provided by ORD and C90.
An SRT will be conducted on Monday, August 23, 2021, at a time to be determined.

SUMMARY.CEDAR: N524DS WAS INBOUND TO ROA ENTERING A RIGHT BASE TO RUNWAY 34 WHEN THEY OBSERVED A LARGE 6 BLADED DRONE AT THEIR 12 O'CLOCK, 100 FEET AHEAD AND 100 FEET BELOW. THE A/C TOOK EVASIVE MANEUVER AND DEVIATED TO THE RIGHT.  THE A/C LANDED SAFELY.
QAFINDINGS.CEDAR: Facility summary, weather and falcon bookmark reviewed. N524DS was inbound to ROA from the east at 2,500ft when the pilot reported a drone passing underneath the aircraft. The pilot reported evasive maneuvers to the right to evade the object and estimated it was 100ft below the aircraft when spotted. Airport operations vehicle was sent to the east end of the airport to search for the object but was unable to see it. Other aircraft in the area were vectored to keep them clear of the reported location. N524DS landed safely and there was no further impact to operations at ROA. DEN, ROC and law enforcement were notified. Preliminary NMAC filed.

LOCAL CONTROL CHANGED NDU752 TO THE RIGHT TRAFFIC PATTER FOR RWY 12R ON THE GO. BOTH DRONES APPEARED SMALL, WITH A STEADY YELLOW LIGHT, AND FLASHING RED AND GREEN LIGHTS. THE DRONES APPEARED TO ORBIT TO THE NORTH-NORTHEAST BEFORE DEPARTING THE AIRSPACE TO THE NORTH.
